the legal "shifting" of a municipal bondholder's claim on an issuer's taxing power or revenues onto another acceptable form of collateral. The municipal issuer will buy U.S. Government securities, Agency securities, or sometimes bank certificates of deposit; escrow them with a trustee; and use the income stream from the escrowed securities to pay the debt service on the outstanding bonds. This effectively removes all bondholder claims against the revenue source backing the original issue and enables the municipality to remove the debt from its balance sheet. The outstanding municipal bonds are now backed by the U.S. Government securities that are held in trust.